CHIKUNGUNYA (41): INDIA (WEST BENGAL)
*************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Wed 1 Oct 2008
Source: The Statesman [edited]
<http://www.thestatesman.net/page.arcview.php?clid=22&id=251793&usrsess=1>


Howrah district [West Bengal state] health administration have
detected chikungunya virus in the blood samples of 8 people in
Baigachi of Howrah district today [1 Oct 2008]. More than 200
residents of Baigachi and its adjacent villages have been suffering
from fever and severe throat pain since 18 Sep [2008].

According to the district health department officials, following the
spread of the disease, experts from the state health administration
visited the affected areas and collected blood samples and serum from
neighbours of the affected people.

According to the chief medical officer, health (CMOH), Howrah, Dr
Dilip Deb: "Blood samples of 10 people in Baigachi were taken and the
district health officials have confirmed that chikungunya [virus?
antibody? - Mod.TY] has been found in the blood samples of 8 people.
All sorts of medical aid are being provided." He further added that
the health department has set up a temporary health care centre at
Baigachi and have started an awareness programme in the area.

The block administration has initiated a drive to control the
breeding of mosquitoes. Medicines are also being distributed among
the villagers. The local primary health centre has been asked to stay
on alert.

--
Communicated by:
Dr Satadal Das, MD, DCP
Consultant Microbiologist
Peerless Hospital & BK Roy Research Centre
76 Satyen Roy Road
Kolkata 700034
India
<drsatdas@hotmail.com>

[ProMED thanks Dr Das for forwarding this article. Interestingly, the
article also states that there were a few dengue virus infections
occurring at the same time, illustrating the need for laboratory
diagnosis to distinguish between these 2 arthropod-borne virus
infections.

